Identity of the Ship User In the Ship of Theseus conundrum, when the ship's boards have all been changed, is it still the Ship of Theseus? And conversely, if you made a Ship using those original boards, does that become the Ship of Theseus? ChatGPT The Ship of Theseus is a classic thought experiment in philosophy that raises questions about identity and persistence over time. The conundrum you describe arises from the following scenario: if all the boards of the Ship of Theseus are gradually replaced, is the resulting ship still the original Ship of Theseus? There is no straightforward answer to this question, as it depends on how one defines the identity of an object. One perspective is that the Ship of Theseus is defined by its material composition, so if all of the original boards are replaced, the ship is no longer the same object. From this point of view, the resulting ship is a new ship made out of different materials, and it cannot be considered the Ship of Theseus. Another perspective is that the Ship of Theseus is defined by its continuity over time, and thus as long as the replacement of boards is gradual, the ship maintains its identity as the Ship of Theseus. From this perspective, the resulting ship is still the Ship of Theseus, despite being made up of new boards. As for the second part of your question, if you were to use the original boards from the Ship of Theseus to construct a new ship, it would not be considered the Ship of Theseus because it is made up of different components. However, it could be seen as a replica or copy of the original Ship of Theseus.

Why does it do that
OOPS! Studio! 2023-05-09 12:48 AM
Ah I can explain why! :) Everything inside Discord has a unique ID. It's called a "snowflake" and it was initially used by Twitter, so it's sometimes referred to as a "Twitter snowflake." A snowflake is essentially just a condensed version of a UUID (Universally Unique ID). Their purpose is to generate a unique number to represent a unique object so that no two objects share the same number. Everything inside Discord has a snowflake ID. Each message has an ID, each emoji has an ID, each user has an ID, each server has an ID, each channel has an ID, etc. Everything has an ID. These snowflakes are 64 bits long. The first 41 bits represent a timestamp - the number of milliseconds since a chosen epoch. Usually, they use the Unix Epoch (12:00 AM on January 1st 1970). The next 10 bits are a "machine ID" which is essentially (I believe) a hash of the machine's MAC address - this ensures that each machine has its own set of IDs to pick from, which removes the need to coordinate these values from machine to machine. The next 12 bits represent a "counter" of sorts, which essentially ensures that multiple snowflakes generated on the same machine in the same millisecond will not clash. The first one will be 0, the next will be 1, then 2, then 3, etc. Then once the next millisecond arrives it resets back to 0. Then finally the last bit is the "sign" of the snowflake - essentially whether it's positive or negative. Then those 64 bits are encoded into a decimal number, and you're left with either 18 to 19 decimal digits. And those digits represent your ID! And so, when you ping someone in Discord, the format for telling Discord to render the text as a ping is to write it like so <@userid>. So for example, Waffle's ID is 1074023184434725044. If I were to ping Waffle, it would look like <@1074023184434725044> (edited)
12:48 AM
12:48 AM
So when Babu textflips a ping, he's really texflipping the text <@1074023184434725044> and that's why you get such a crazy and ugly response. When he then textflips it back, he ends up writing out <@1074023184434725044> which Discord automatically converts into a ping! You can also use the format of <#channelid> to ping channels. For example, owlnest's ID is 1030660521172676668, so <#1030660521172676668> will come out as #╭🦉・owlnest

Snowflake IDs, or snowflakes, are a form of unique identifier used in distributed computing. The format was created by Twitter and is used for the IDs of tweets. The format has been adopted by other companies, including Discord and Instagram. The Mastodon social network uses a modified version.
